gn=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ashraveneq>AshravenEQ</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/17/03 6:05:32 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm45.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=85.topic&index=5>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Mark of Karn</span><hr size=1> I'm a big big fan of Mark of Karn.  Specially with the uber-hit point mobs that take over a minute to kill.  Hunting in the Umbral Plain (or any of the planes), I make an effort to Mark of Karn and/or Mark of Retribution the critter.<br>
<br>
Reason?  Mana conservation.  You won't notice the primary tank growing health faster than normal (albeit with an excellent slower/haster present you actually do) but they *will* lose health slower.  I'm having to drop complete heals on our tank a lot quicker rwhen the monster has no Mark of Karn than when the critter has been tagged.<br>
<br>
I guess it depends on strategy on healing.  If a warrior has 40 or 8000 hit points I don't care...I just look at it as &quot;one red bar&quot;.  When they start getting hit I start counting to myself to see how much health they are losing per ten seconds.  This gives me an idea of when to start the complete heal to be the most mana efficient while having enough buffer to cover the odd damage-spike.<br>
<br>
With Mark of Karn my counts reveal that I don't have to heal as quickly into the fight.  Less heals means more mana conservation and more mana conservation means more fights before that inevitable &quot;mana break please&quot; call.<br>
<br>
You will really see Mark of Karn come into its own when your tank is paired with a hasted monk or rogue.  Even the odd riposte from the creature is quickly recovered and you don't have to send out a heal to cover the extra fighters.   Even other non-speedy melees benifit from the influx of health and you'll spend less time topping them off and more time focused on the main tank.<br>
<br>
I also try to get Mark of Retribution off as soon as possible in the fight.  15 points may not sound much but every addition to the damage-per-seconds while I can sit back and med is a plus in my book.<br>
<br>
Mark of Karn isn't worth casting on critters that take less than thirty seconds to kill.  Specifically raid situations where you're clearing out the trash before the boss and the melees are gang-smacking the adds.   They die too quickly to make an impact worth the mana.<br>
<br>
Ashraven <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ashraveneq>AshravenEQ</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 3<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/18/03 2:29:11 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm45.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=85.topic&index=6>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Mark of Karn</span><hr size=1> And Mark of Karn lasts for 3 minutes when it connects with a mob, healing anybody who's hitting the critter 6 hit points a pop.  It doesn't just heal once and fade for that person.<br>
